            <h2>Alibaba cloud revenue grows 38% as AI-related products reach 30% of external customer revenue</h2>
            <div class="plain-text">
              <p>Alibaba, the Chinese technology company that owns the Alibaba Cloud computing platform, reported Cloud Intelligence Group revenue of RMB 41,626 million ($6.04 billion) in the March 2026 quarter, marking a 38% increase Y-o-Y. AI-related product revenue achieved its eleventh consecutive quarter of triple-digit growth, and AI products now account for 30% of external cloud customer revenue. Profitability declined significantly: core adjusted EBITA fell 84% to RMB 5.1 billion ($740 million), driven by simultaneous investments in quick commerce, the Qwen app's user acquisition, and AI infrastructure. Cloud Intelligence Group's adjusted EBITA rose 57% despite heavy capital expenditure. CEO Eddie Wu stated the company launched Wukong, an AI-native enterprise agent, and fully integrated Taobao e-commerce into the consumer-facing Qwen app. The company reaffirmed $53 billion in AI and cloud capital expenditure over 3 years, deploying $5.4 billion in the past quarter alone. Cloud external revenue growth accelerated to 40%. </p>
            </div>
            <div class="why-matters">
              <strong>Why it matters</strong>Cloud now carries Alibaba's growth narrative as e-commerce margin compresses, but profitability sacrificed for AI adoption shows Chinese hyperscalers are building multi-year positions rather than harvesting near-term returns. The 30% AI penetration rate sets a high-water mark for enterprise AI monetization outside the US The spending trajectory – $53 billion committed, quarterly capital expenditure rising – confirms Chinese technology platforms are establishing AI sovereignty ahead of any Western regulatory or technology export constraints.
            </div>
