            <h2>AI voice startup Vapi raises $50 million at $500 million valuation after Amazon Ring deploys platform for 100% of inbound calls</h2>
            <div class="plain-text">
              <p>Vapi, a startup that builds AI voice platforms for customer support, closed a $50 million Series B led by Peak XV Partners at a $500 million post-money valuation, bringing total funding to $72 million. Amazon Ring, the home security company owned by Amazon, routes 100% of its inbound customer support calls through Vapi's voice AI platform after evaluating more than 40 competing vendors during the 2025 holiday season surge. Vapi has processed over 1 billion calls through its platform and currently handles between 1–5 million calls daily, with enterprise customers including Intuit, New York Life, Instawork, and Kavak. The startup has approximately 100 employees and operates a self-serve developer platform used by more than 1 million developers. Annual recurring revenue is in the "healthy" eight figures. Co-founder and CEO Jordan Dearsley said Ring chose Vapi because the platform gave internal engineering teams granular control over AI agent behavior in live customer interactions without depending on engineering support. Ring's Vice President of Software Development Jason Mitura stated customer satisfaction scores improved after deploying Vapi's platform. Microsoft's M12, Kleiner Perkins, and Bessemer Venture Partners participated in the round.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="why-matters">
              <strong>Why it matters</strong>Amazon choosing a third-party voice AI vendor over building in-house signals that even resource-rich enterprises now view voice infrastructure as a commodity layer where speed-to-deployment beats vertical integration. Ring processing 100% of inbound traffic through Vapi establishes a new operational benchmark: voice AI is no longer a pilot program but the default call routing decision for seasonal capacity planning. The 1 billion call volume and eight-figure annual recurring revenue validate that AI voice economics – cost per call, accuracy, and customer satisfaction – now compete with traditional call center outsourcing at scale.
            </div>
            <div class="indicators-block">
              <div class="section-label">Key numbers</div>
