            <h2>OpenAI launches $4 billion Deployment Company to scale enterprise AI adoption with 19 investment partners</h2>
            <div class="plain-text">
              <p>OpenAI, the company that made ChatGPT, announced the OpenAI Deployment Company, a new entity majority-owned and controlled by OpenAI, capitalized with $4 billion from 19 global investment firms, consultancies, and system integrators and valued at $10 billion. The company will help organizations integrate AI systems into core infrastructure and workflows, redesign business processes around AI, and convert pilot programs to production systems. Capgemini, one of the world's largest technology consulting firms, announced an investment in the entity, citing its position to support scaled AI deployment across industries. OpenAI also announced plans to acquire applied AI consulting firm Tomoro, which will bring ~150 forward-deployed engineers and deployment specialists to the Deployment Company once the transaction closes. Chief Revenue Officer Denise Dresser stated that AI is "becoming capable of doing increasingly meaningful work inside organizations" and the challenge is helping companies integrate systems into infrastructure and workflows. Enterprise now represents more than 40 percent of OpenAI's revenue, and the company projects that portion will reach parity with consumer by the end of 2026.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="why-matters">
              <strong>Why it matters</strong>OpenAI structuring enterprise deployment as a separate $10 billion entity capitalized by consulting giants signals that scaling AI beyond proof-of-concept is now a services business, not just a model licensing opportunity. The $4 billion raise dedicated to services infrastructure – not model training – reveals where capital allocation friction actually sits: enterprises need integration labor, not better models. The 150-person Tomoro acquisition and plans for additional services firm acquisitions confirm the bottleneck is execution capacity, not technology maturity. Enterprise revenue reaching 40% with parity projected by year-end means OpenAI's growth now depends on deployment velocity as much as model performance.
            </div>
