            </div>
            <h2>Cloudflare cuts 1,100 workers as AI usage surges 600% in 3 months despite record revenue growth</h2>
            <div class="plain-text">
              <p>Cloudflare, the web infrastructure and security company, announced it will eliminate more than 1,100 employees globally, approximately 20% of its workforce, as part of an AI-driven restructuring. CEO Matthew Prince and President Michelle Zatlyn stated the company's internal AI usage increased by more than 600% in the past 3 months, with employees across engineering, HR, finance, and marketing running thousands of AI agent sessions daily. The layoffs were announced the same day Cloudflare reported Q1 2026 revenue of $639.8 million, up 34% Y-o-Y and beating Wall Street estimates, but shares fell more than 20% following the announcement. The company will incur restructuring charges of $140 million to $150 million in Q2 2026. Affected employees will receive full base pay through the end of 2026, extended healthcare coverage, and accelerated equity vesting through August 15. Prince stated on the earnings call that the company expects to hire more employees in 2027 than it had at any point in 2026, but the roles are "changing dramatically." CFO Thomas Seifert noted that all teams and geographies were affected except salespeople who carry revenue quotas. Prince acknowledged the company initially resisted internal AI adoption but reached a "tipping point" in November 2025 when teams began seeing productivity gains of two, ten, or even 100 times previous levels.</p>
