            <h2>South Korea proposes "national dividend" tax on AI profits as semiconductor boom drives record earnings</h2>
            <div class="plain-text">
              <p>South Korean Senior Presidential Secretary for Policy Kim Yong-beom proposed a tax on artificial intelligence profits for social redistribution as Samsung Electronics and SK Hynix posted record first-quarter earnings from AI chip demand. Kim warned that South Korea is shifting from a traditional export economy toward a "technology monopoly economy" driven by chip scarcity and sustained excess profits, stating the transition could deepen societal polarization. He tentatively called the policy a "national dividend" that would redistribute excess corporate profits from AI technology to fund start-up support for young people, basic income programs for rural and fishing communities, artist support, and pension strengthening. South Korea's benchmark KOSPI has rallied over the past month, repeatedly hitting record highs, and briefly approached the key 8,000-point mark. The proposal follows demands from Samsung Electronics' labor union for removal of caps on performance bonuses and implementation of a system allocating 15% of operating profit to bonuses. South Korean lawmaker Moon Geum-ju argued last month that the semiconductor boom was built partly on "the sacrifice and patience of farmers and fishermen" and that profits should be returned to rural communities. Global AI data center construction has driven soaring demand for advanced high-bandwidth memory chips. South Korea announced it would triple AI spending this year, targeting a position among the top three AI powers alongside the US and China.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="why-matters">
              <strong>Why it matters</strong>A senior presidential adviser in the world's leading memory chip exporter floating an AI profit tax signals governments are moving from AI safety regulation to wealth redistribution policy as first-order chips dominate global AI infrastructure buildout. Kim's proposal comes as South Korea captures asymmetric AI economic gains through Samsung and SK Hynix's near-monopoly in high-bandwidth memory production, creating political pressure to socialize windfall profits before they concentrate further. The timing – during a sustained KOSPI rally and record corporate earnings – suggests redistributive AI policy will emerge during boom cycles, not downturns, as governments attempt to capture economic rents before they calcify into structural inequality.
            </div>
