      <p>Alibaba converting Cloud Intelligence Group into a growth driver while sacrificing core profitability, OpenAI raising $4 billion for services infrastructure separate from model development, and Vapi capturing $500 million in enterprise voice AI valuation all signal that deployment, integration, and operational control – not model performance – now drive competitive moats. Cloudflare's 20% workforce cut during a 34% revenue growth quarter makes explicit what others will euphemize: AI productivity gains are being harvested as margin expansion, not reinvestment. South Korea's proposed AI profit tax responds directly to this pattern, attempting to recapture economic rents before they escape democratic accountability. Organizations that treat this issue as five independent stories rather than a single structural transition will misallocate capital, underinvest in deployment capacity, and remain exposed to policy risk as governments move from regulating AI safety to redistributing AI wealth.</p>
